Load Datasets

# load brewery data CSV file
breweries <- read.csv('Breweries.csv', encoding = 'UTF-8') %>% 
  # trim white space around the state abbreviation
  mutate(State=str_trim(State))

# load beer data from CSV file
beer <- read.csv('Beers.csv',  encoding = 'UTF-8')

# load city, state geolocation data from csv file
cities <- read.csv('us_cities.csv') %>% select(-COUNTY) %>%
  rename(CITY_LAT=LATITUDE, CITY_LON=LONGITUDE)

# load state populations
populations <- read.csv('state_populations.csv') %>% 
  mutate(State=str_to_lower(State))

# join geolocation to brewery data
breweries <- left_join(breweries, cities, by=c('City'='CITY', 'State'='STATE_CODE'))

Breweries Per State

How many breweries are present in each state?

# change the state column from a <chr> to a <fctr> and count the breweries
breweries_by_state <- breweries %>% 
  mutate(State=factor(State)) %>% 
  count(State)

# calculate average number of breweries by state
average_breweries_by_state <- mean(breweries_by_state$n)
  
# create bar chart of breweries by state
breweries_by_state %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=reorder(State, n), y=n)) +
    # add the average number of breweries
    geom_hline(yintercept=average_breweries_by_state, color='#DD1731') + 
    geom_text(
      x=2, 
      y=average_breweries_by_state + 3.5, 
      label='Average', 
      color='#DD1731'
    ) +
    # add lines for lollipop chart
    geom_segment(aes(xend=State, yend=0), color='#bdc3c7') +
    # add points for lollipop chart
    geom_point(size=3, color='#DD1731') +
    # flip bars from x to y axis
    coord_flip() +
    # add title, x-axis, and y-axis label 
    labs(x='', y='', title='Number of Breweries by State') +
    # remove background and format text
    theme(
      panel.background = element_blank(),
      panel.grid.major=element_blank(),
      panel.grid.minor=element_blank(),
      plot.title = element_text(size=28, color='#DD1731'),
      axis.text=element_text(size=12),
      axis.title=element_text(size=20)
    )

Plot the Number of Breweries by State on a Map

# count the number of breweries by state
brewery_counts <- breweries %>% 
  mutate(State=str_to_lower(STATE_NAME)) %>% 
  count(State) 

# create per capita brewery count
breweries_by_population <- brewery_counts %>%
  left_join(populations, by='State') %>%
  mutate(per_capita = n / Population)

# create variables for map data
usa <- map_data('usa')
states <- map_data('state')

# join the brewery counts to the state shape data
state_breweries <- left_join(states, brewery_counts, by=c('region'='State'))

# plot the data on a US map with state lines
state_breweries %>% ggplot(aes(x=long, y=lat, group=group)) + 
  geom_polygon(aes(fill=n), color='white') +

# analyze missing values in the combined dataset
df_missing <- df %>% 
  # Select the column if missing values exist
  select_if(function(x) any(is.na(x))) %>%
  # summarize the number of missing values in each column
  summarise_all(funs(sum(is.na(.)))) %>%
  # gather all missing value columns 
  gather(col_name, missing_count) %>%
  # calculate percentages of missing values in a new column 
  mutate(missing_percent = missing_count / nrow(df) * 100,)

Median ABV and IBU Comparison by State

Compute the median ABV and IBU for each state and compare using a bar chart.

# start with the cleaned dataframe
df_clean %>% 
  # group by the state
  group_by(State) %>%
  # add statistics for the median ABV and median IBU
  summarize('ABV (Median)'=median(ABV), 'IBU (Median)'=median(IBU)) %>% 
  # gather new columns into key-value pairs
  gather(statistic, val, c('ABV (Median)', 'IBU (Median)')) %>%
  # create plot to compare median ABV and IBU values between states
  ggplot(aes(x=reorder(State, val), y=val)) +
    # add bar geometry to the plot
    # geom_bar(stat='identity', fill='#DD1731', width=0.6, alpha=0.8) +
    # add lines for lollipop chart
    geom_segment(aes(xend=State, yend=0), color='#bdc3c7') +
    # add points for lollipop chart
    geom_point(size=3, color='#DD1731') +
    # flip the bars to be horizontal
    coord_flip() + 
    # create separate facets for the measurements
    facet_wrap(~statistic, nrow=1, scales='free') +
    # remove background and format text
    theme(
      legend.position = 'none',
      plot.title = element_text(size=24, color='#DD1731'),
      panel.background = element_blank(),
      panel.grid.major=element_blank(),
      panel.grid.minor=element_blank(),
      axis.text=element_text(size=12),
      axis.title=element_text(size=20)
    ) +
    # add plot title, x, and y labels
    labs(
      title='Median ABV and IBU by State',
      x='State',
      y='Measurement Value'
    )

Maximum ABV and IBU Values Overall

Find the states with the highest ABV and IBU values.

n <- 8

# calculate the maximum ABV value for each state
max_abv_by_state <- df_clean %>% 
  group_by(State) %>%
  summarize(ABV_max=max(ABV))

# plot the top n ABV states
max_abv_by_state %>% 
  arrange(desc(ABV_max)) %>% head(n) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=reorder(State, ABV_max), y=ABV_max)) +
    geom_bar(stat='identity', fill='#DD1731', width=0.6) +
    gghighlight(State == 'KY') +
    # flip the bars to be horizontal
    coord_flip() +
    # remove background and format text
    theme(
      plot.title = element_text(size=22, color='#DD1731'),
      panel.background = element_blank(),
      panel.grid.major=element_blank(),
      panel.grid.minor=element_blank(),
      axis.text=element_text(size=12),
      axis.title=element_text(size=20)
    ) +
    # add plot title, x, and y labels
    labs(
      title=paste('Top', n, 'Maximum ABV Values by State', sep=' '),
      x='State',
      y='ABV (Max.)'
    )

# calculate the maximum IBU value for each state
max_ibu_by_state <- df_clean %>% 
  group_by(State) %>%
  summarize(IBU_max=max(IBU))

# plot the top n IBU states
max_ibu_by_state %>% 
  arrange(desc(IBU_max)) %>% head(n) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=reorder(State, IBU_max), y=IBU_max)) +
    geom_bar(stat='identity', fill='#DD1731', width=0.6) +
    gghighlight(State == 'OR') +
    # flip the bars to be horizontal
    coord_flip() +
    # remove background and format text
    theme(
      plot.title = element_text(size=22, color='#DD1731'),
      panel.background = element_blank(),
      panel.grid.major=element_blank(),
      panel.grid.minor=element_blank(),
      axis.text=element_text(size=12),
      axis.title=element_text(size=20)
    ) +
    # add plot title, x, and y labels
    labs(
      title=paste('Top', n, 'Maximum IBU Values by State', sep=' '),
      x='State',
      y='IBU (Max.)'
    )

Bitterness and Alcohol Content

Use a scatter plot to investigate if there is an apparent relationship between the bitterness of the beer and its alcoholic content.

# create an x-y plot using the cleaned data
df_clean %>% ggplot(aes(x=ABV, y=IBU)) +
  # add a jitter to the points to view overlapping data
  geom_jitter(shape=1, alpha=0.95, color='#DD1731') + 
  # add a trend line to the data
  geom_smooth(formula='y~x', method='lm', color='#e67e22') +
  # remove background and format text
  theme(
    legend.position = 'none',
    plot.title = element_text(size=18, color='#DD1731'),
    panel.background = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.major=element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor=element_blank()
  ) + 
  # add axis titles
  labs(
    title='IBU vs ABV with Linear Model Trendline', 
    x='Alcohol by Volume (ABV)', 
    y='International Bitterness Units (IBU)',
  )

  mutate(beer_region = ifelse(Style %in% german_beers, 'German', 'Others')) %>%
